description: {"blocks":[{"key":"5b6p7","text":"This protocol details the assembly of peptide-MHC dextramers for use in downstream applications, including flow cytometric detection or magnetic enrichment of T cells specific for a given peptide-MHC (pMHC). Dextramer assembly of biotinylated pMHC is performed by doping onto a dextran backbone using an economic method described previously. The resulting high valency pMHC dextramers enable profiling of immune responses that may prove difficult to detect using conventional pMHC tetramers.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"3287r","text":"This protocol details the assembly of peptide-MHC dextramers for use in flow cytometric detection or magnetic enrichment of T cells specific for a given peptide-MHC (pMHC). pMHC are generated via UV-exchange and multimerized onto a dextran backbone, which can be functionalized with any fluorophore-conjugated streptavidin. This protocol is adapted from the methods originally described by Rodenko et al. (2006) and Bethune et al. (2017).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":390,"length":21},{"key":1,"offset":416,"length":21}],"data":{}},{"key":"52v8e","text":"    UV exchange of peptide-MHC complexes enables the exchange of any antigenic peptide of interest in complex with a given recombinant MHC1. Herein, we use commercially produced biotinylated MHC monomers complexed with UV-cleavable peptides. However, recombinant protein production methods can be performed by the user to produce their own biotinylated MHC monomers1. UV-exchange technology affords the benefit of assembling several distinct pMHC specificities from a single batch of recombinant pMHC. Furthermore, these specificities can be assayed simultaneously in a single sample using combinatorial fluorophore barcoding2,3. The use of small molecule dye streptavidin conjugates (Streptavidin-AF647, Streptavidin-FITC) is not recommended.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"sup","offset":138,"length":1},{"style":"sup","offset":365,"length":1},{"style":"sup","offset":625,"length":3}],"entityRanges":[{"key":2,"offset":724,"length":18}],"data":{}},{"key":"8kf9t","text":"    Dextramer assembly of biotinylated pMHC is performed by doping onto a dextran backbone using an economic method described previously4. In essence, the doping strategy involves substoichiometric assembly of no more than 3 pMHC molecules per streptavidin-fluorophore conjugate, and subsequent doping in of dextran-biotin to saturate the remnant biotin binding site on the streptavidin. In contrast to pMHC tetramers, which only afford a valency of four pMHC complexes per tetramer molecule, pMHC dextramers afford higher-order valencies which increase the signal-to-noise ratio of detection in a manner correlated with the molecular weight of the dextran backbone5. Herein, we use a 500 kDa dextran-biotin backbone, which has an empirically determined degree of biotinylation of 40 molecules per backbone6. Using the dextran doping strategy, a valency of 120 pMHC molecules per dextran backbone is theoretically possible.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"sup","offset":136,"length":1},{"style":"sup","offset":665,"length":1},{"style":"sup","offset":806,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ckpj6","text":"    The resulting high valency pMHC dextramers enable profiling of immune responses that may otherwise be undetectable. These dextramers can be used for magnetic enrichment using anti-fluorochrome magnetic beads to isolate and culture rare, antigen-specific T cells from human or animal specimen. The use of pre-enrichment, especially from a large sample, reduces the amount of cell culture media and cytokines needed in downstream  culture. Staining can be further enhanced through the use of dasatinib pre-incubation and anti-fluorochrome antibody labeling7.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"sup","offset":558,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"CEABBBF0CB5611ECA67247C986F63D54","url":"https://www.nature.com/articles/nprot.2006.121"}},"1":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"E11D9100CB5611ECA67247C986F63D54","url":"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28298179/"}},"2":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"62552830226611EDB251438FBC9DEC2C","url":"https://www.nature.com/articles/nri3020"}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"5lfi1","text":"Materials:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ta6i","text":"Biotinylated MHC monomer refolded with UV-cleavable peptide","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ae59u","text":"Antigenic peptide of interest","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ahbi4","text":"Dextran-biotin MW 500 kDa (Nanocs cat# DX500-BN-1), reconstituted in PBS","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"bml50","text":"Fluorophore-conjugated streptavidin of choice (e.g. Streptavidin-PE, Streptavidin-APC, Streptavidin-BV785)","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8cteo","text":"D-Biotin","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cr983","text":"Sodium azide","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6kusv","text":"96-well V-bottom polystyrene or polypropylene plate","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5udbc","text":"RPMI + 10-20% FBS","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2f73o","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"43bbd","text":"Equipment:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"vdcj","text":"365nm UV lamp ","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"fg6pf","text":"Peptide exchange:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cjm6b","text":"Block the wells of a 96-well V-bottom plate with 200uL of RPMI + 10-20% FBS. Add media, incubate briefly (a few seconds to minutes) and remove and discard all media.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6vl9","text":"Add MHC monomer and peptide to a final concentration of 4uM and 100-1000 ug/mL, respectively, in a well of the 96-well plate.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ahv38","text":"Place plate on ice with 365nm UV lamp 2-5cm above plate, or as close as possible. Cover lamp and plate with foil to protect surroundings.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5m7u2","text":"Irradiate for 30 min to 1hr on ice. Exchange reaction efficiency is dependent on several factors, including: affinity of peptide for MHC, volume of reaction in well, and ability of reaction ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"25a33","text":"Add streptavidin conjugate (e.g. Streptavidin-PE) to the exchange reaction to a 2.5-3:1 molar ratio of MHC:Streptavidin. Use the concentration of streptavidin component only, excluding the fluorophore, to calculate the ratio. Use the initial concentration of the MHC component, which is biotinylated at a 1:1 molar ratio of MHC:biotin when biotinylated by conventional Avitag biotinylation by BirA. Assume. Do not perform dropwise addition as the goal in this step is to assemble low order pMHC-streptavidin complexes.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"j1i6","text":"Incubate 15 min. on ice.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4garq","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9mk03","text":"Dextran doping:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"qjco","text":"Add dextran-biotin to a molar ratio of 20:1 streptavidin:dextran-biotin. Again, use only the streptavidin component of the conjugate to calculate molar mass. The biotin component weight of the dextran-biotin is negligible relative to the backbone (9.76 kDa biotin per 500 kDa dextran-biotin backbone, assuming 40 biotin sites per backbone).","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"l3al","text":"Incubate 15 min. on ice","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"214kv","text":"Block the reaction by adding D-Biotin to a final concentration of 25-30uM and sodium azide to a final concentration of 0.02% wt/vol.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2abo","text":"Store at 4C and use the dextramer at 1-10ug/mL pMHC final concentration when staining cells, calculated based on initial monomer concentration. Before use, spin the dextramer at 10,000xg - 20,000xg at 4C for 1-2min to pellet aggregates, and use the supernatant to stain cells.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"f3lf1","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"eq235","text":"Assumptions are made in the above protocol, which may be sources of error depending on the model system being investigated (i.e. choice of peptide and MHC allotype):","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4ca05","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2ab94","text":"It is assumed that 100% of MHC is rescued during UV-exchange. If the peptide of interest is not sufficiently affine for cognate MHC, higher concentrations of peptide may be necessary to achieve close to 100% rescue. ELISA can be used to determine the extent of MHC stabilization when exchanged with the peptide of interest. In practice, we use TAP-deficient T2 cells expressing the MHC allele of interest to determine MHC stabilization by FACS after an overnight peptide pulse.","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"jd4p","text":"The MW distribution of dextran-biotin is assumed to be normally distributed with a mean MW of 500 kDa. Without confirmation by HPLC, the possibility that lower or higher MW dextran backbones are present cannot be ruled out.","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6n1ms","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
